</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="74" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="8.[99,1307,288,914]" pageId="8" pageNumber="74">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[101,810,606,635]" pageId="8" pageNumber="74">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
This species has not been studied in the wild.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="74" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="8.[99,1307,288,914]" pageId="8" pageNumber="74">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[101,449,680,713]" pageId="8" pageNumber="74">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
CITES Appendix I. Classified as Data Deficient on The [UCN Red List. However, at the [IUCN/SSC Lemur Red-Listing Workshop held in July 2012, L. ahmansonorum was assessed as endangered. The Tsiombikibo Sportive Lemur is not known to occur in any protected areas, but it is found in the Tsiombikibo Classified Forest, which provides some protection.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
